description: Test if Θ_lab (applied only to fifth-force) shifts bottleneck from fifth-force to collider limits
key_finding: Differential screening does NOT shift bottleneck. All runs remain 100% fifth-force limited.

explanation.why_no_shift: Alpha values in viable region are extremely small (1e-12 to 1e-8), making fifth-force slack ~1e-6 (tight) while collider slacks are ~0.1 (loose). Even with screening reducing effective alpha by 100×, fifth-force remains the tightest constraint.
explanation.collider_constraints: Collider constraints (ATLAS μ, Higgs inv) have slacks ~0.1, which is 100,000× larger than fifth-force slacks. They never become the bottleneck.
explanation.conclusion: Fifth-force constraints dominate so hard that even differential screening cannot shift the bottleneck. Need scale-breaking suppression (μ parameter) to allow larger alpha while evading fifth-force bounds.
